Bubble sorting is a simple sorting algorithm that works by repeatedly iterating through the array, comparing adjacent elements, and swapping them if they are in the wrong order. Here's the algorithm in C++ code format:
```cpp
void bubbleSort(int arr[], int n) {
    for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < n - i - 1; j++) {
            if (arr[j] > arr[j + 1]) {
                int temp = arr[j];
                arr[j] = arr[j + 1];
                arr[j + 1] = temp;
            }
        }
    }
}

int main() {

    int arr[5] = { 3, 2, 5, 8, 1 };

    bubbleSort(arr, 5);

    for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {

        printf("%d\n", arr[i]);

    }

    return 0;

}

```

In this code, we define a function `bubbleSort` that takes an array `arr` of `n` integers and its size `n` as input, and sorts the array in ascending order using the bubble sorting algorithm.

The function first iterates through the array `arr` from the first index `i = 0` to the last index `i = n - 1`, and at each iteration, it compares the element at index `j` with the element at index `j + 1`. If the element at index `j` is smaller than the element at index `j + 1`, they are swapped using the statement `arr[j] = arr[j + 1];`.

The function repeats this process of comparing and swapping elements until it completes the last iteration, at which point it exits the loop.

